name: Sligachan, Isle of Skye
description:
The Black Cuillin reflected in a lochan near the walking centre of Sligachan on the Isle of Skye, Scotland.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 Prints only):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame

name: Glencoe mist
description:
Taken around 4am from the hills to the north of Glencoe, the high mountains around Bidean nam Beinn rise up from the early morning mist.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x9”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Quiraing, Isle of Skye
description:
The Quiraing on the northern part of the Isle of Skye is one of the most photographed areas on the island.
Formed by a series of huge landslips, the area has featured in many major films and TV shows over the years.


* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Mealt Falls, Isle of Skye
description:
Mealt Falls, Isle of Skye  Scotland

Situated on the Trotternish peninsular of the Isle of Skye, Mealt Falls and nearby Kilt Rock form a spectacular setting as Loch Mealt drains over a 200ft cliff into The Minch.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Greenan Castle, Ayrshire
description:
Greenan Castle is a 16th Century tower house overlooking Greenan shore, 2.5 miles south west of Ayr.
The castle and it’s story of ambush and murder in 1603 inspired Sir Walter Scott to write a short play, “An Ayrshire Tragedy”

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: St Andrews Castle, Scotland
description:
There has been a castle on this site in the Royal Burgh of St Andrews since the late 12th Century.
Over the years it has served as a Bishops palace, army stronghold, Royal residence, prison, and more recently, a tourist attraction.

Sieges over the years have taken their toll and the castle is now a ruin.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Robert the Bruce with rainbow, Stirling
description:
Standing in the esplanade of Stirling Castle, the statue of King Robert the Bruce gazes out while behind the low winter sun lights a bright rainbow over the Ochil Hills. 

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: The Hermitage, Perthshire
description:
Located in Craigvinean Forest, near the town of Dunkeld, The Hermitage is a beautiful series of walks around the River Braan.
Several Georgian follies (Ossian’s cave and Ossian’s Hall of Mirrors) built by the Dukes of Atholl in the 18th Century were created to honour the mythical Gaelic poet Ossian. 

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Forest path, Scottish Borders
description:
The forest of Cardrona in the Scottish Borders is a beautiful mixed conifer woodland, perched on a hill overlooking the famous Salmon fishing river Tweed.
This shot was taken close to the remains of the ancient Iron Age fort of Castle Knowe and the ruined 16th Century Cardrona Tower.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Birks of Aberfeldy
description:
Scotland’s national bard, Robert Burns, visited the mixed woodland around the Falls of Moness, Aberfeldy, in 1787 and was so inspired that he wrote “The Birks of Aberfeldy”
Taken just below the summit of the walk, the early morning Autumn sun lights the spray from the falls to give this image an “otherworldly” feel.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Rannoch Moor
description:
Clach Leathad and the distant Aonach Mor tower above the flat expanse of Rannoch Moor, site of the last significant ice-field in the UK at the end of the last ice-age.
Low winter sun picks out the moorland colours while the distant mountains sit under a brooding storm cloud.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Black Mount, Rannoch Moor
description:
The Black Mount is a mountain range between Glen Orchy and Glencoe.  Taken from the Great Moor of Rannoch, this image shows Stob a’Choire Odhair as seen from near Lochan na h-Achlaise.

Featured in Robert Louis Stevenson’s classic novel “Kidnapped”, Rannoch Moor and the Black Mount are one of my favourite locations.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Glencoe blizzard
description:
Stob nan Cabar of Buachaille Etive Beag (Little Shepherd of Etive) rises out of the Lairig Gartain pass between Glencoe and Glen Etive.
A late winter blizzard heightens the feeling of isolation in this ancient landscape.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Loch Lubnaig dawn
description:
Loch Lubnaig lies in the valley between Ben Ledi and Ben Vorlich, close to the town of Callander in Scotland.
Taken near the southern point, where the loch drains into the River Leny, this image captures the rising mist and cold pre-dawn light on the forested slopes of Ben Ledi.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Inveraray sunset
description:
The town of Inveraray on Loch Fyne is the ancestral home of the Duke’s of Argyll., chiefs of the Clan Campbell.
A popular tourist spot, the town boasts a Castle and a museum which is now housed in the old Jail.
Taken from the western shore near to the castle, this image shows the sun setting behind the town.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Sallochy Bay, Loch Lomond
description:
A cold and wet day at Sallochy Bay on the eastern shores of Loch Lomond.
Heavy rain clouds hang over the distant isle of Inchlonaig (“Yew tree island”)

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Old Bridge, The Hermitage
description:
Located in Craigvinean Forest, near the town of Dunkeld, The Hermitage is a beautiful series of walks around the River Braan.

The old bridge sits just below the dramatic waterfall close to Ossians Hall of Mirrors.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Falls of Falloch
description:
The Falls of Falloch is a popular picnic spot in Glen Falloch, to the north of Loch Lomond.
A beautiful natural deep pool has been carved by the falls and is popular with kayakers and swimmers.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Glencoe waterfall
description:
Close to the picturesque Loch Achtriochtan, the River Coe falls in a series of dramatic steps against a backdrop of the Glencoe mountains.
To the right, the buttress of Aonach Dubh rises out of the valley, while to the left of the image is the Aonach Eagach ridge, generally regarded as the most difficult scrambling ridge in Scotland.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Balmaha after the storm, Loch Lomond
description:
Taken close to the village of Balmaha on the eastern shores of Loch Lomond just after a storm, the normally calm waters of Loch Lomond are churned by the gale force winds.
The sun breaks through the storm clouds just above the wooded slopes of Inchcailloch.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Ellen's Isle,Loch Katrine
description:
Loch Katrine is the main source of drinking water for the city of Glasgow and is a popular day-trip destination.

Ellen’s isle sits just off the northern shore of the loch, near the main visitor centre.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Lochan Spling
description:
Situated in the Loch Ard forest, close to the town of Aberfoyle, Lochan Spling is a beautiful small loch, popular with anglers and walkers.

Taken on a bright day in late autumn, the glass-like surface of the loch reflects the surrounding forest.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Camas Daraich, Isle of Skye
description:
Camas Daraich is a beautiful sandy beach close to the Point of Sleat, the southern-most point on the Isle of Skye.
Taken from the rocks to the north of the bay and looking east towards the distant mainland, this image shows the beautiful clear waters of the bay.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Neist Point, Isle of Skye
description:
Neist Point is the most westerly point on the Isle of Skye.  
Popular with walkers, photographers and bird-watchers, the area is ideal for whale and dolphin watching.
Taken from near the car-park this image shows An t-Aigeach (The Stallion) which marks the western most point.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Mull of Galloway
description:
The Mull of Galloway is the southern-most point in Scotland and the dramatic cliffs which drop into the Irish Sea are home to a wide variety of sea-birds and other wildlife.
This is taken near the lighthouse looking west, back along the Scottish mainland.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Fat Sams at Isleornsay
description:
“Fat Sams” lies berthed in the reeds of the sheltered bay of Isleornsay on the Sleat peninsula of the Isle of Skye.
Taken early on a spring morning, the soft dawn light adds a sense of calm to the image.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Ballantrae
description:
Taken near the village of Ballantrae on the south Ayrshire coast, this long exposure shot captures the movement of the tide around the rocky shore.
Just beyond the rocks to the right of the image lies the cave of the infamous Alexander “Sawney” Bean, mass-murdering cannibal from the 15th Century who allegedly killed - and ate - over 1000 people here!

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Sallochy sunset
description:
The sun sets behind the Luss hills to the west of Loch Lomond as seen from Sallochy bay on the eastern shore of the loch.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x9”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Isleornsay sunset
description:
The sun sets on the Isleornsay lighthouse and distant Scottish mainland as seen from Isleornsay, Isle of Skye.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x9”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Approaching storm, Mull of Galloway
description:
The Mull of Galloway is the southern-most point in Scotland and on a clear day the view includes parts of Scotland, Northern Ireland, England and the Isle of Man.   This shot was taken as a storm swept towards the Scottish mainland from the Irish Sea.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
18x9”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in 40x60cm black wooden frame.

name: Glencoe sunset
description:
The setting sun bursts through low cloud in three bright crepuscular rays along the Lairig Gartain between Buachaille Etive Beag and Buachaille Etive Mor in Glencoe, Scotland.
The nearby Lochan na Fola means “The Little Loch of Blood” and gives some clues to the violent history of this beautiful landscape. 

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: Wee Peter, Loch Lomond
description:
In the cove of Aldochlay to the south of the village of Luss, Loch Lomond, the statue of a young boy stands alone in the morning mist.
“Wee Peter” was placed in the Loch by a London stonemason in 1890.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: Falls of Clyde
description:
Taken near Corra Linn, the largest waterfall in the Falls of Clyde complex, near the UNESCO world heritage site of New Lanark, this shot was taken at the point where the river transforms from a slow, smooth flowing river to a raging torrent.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: Loch Fyne sunset
description:
The sun sets over Loch Fyne, Argyll as seen from the village of Furnace, to the south of Inveraray.

* LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: River Etive and Stob Dubh
description:
The River Etive falls in deep pools and eddies as it flows through Glen Etive on route to the sea loch of Loch Etive.

Taken near Dalness, the peak of Stob Dubh rises up behind the falls.

*LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: Pucks Glen02, Scotland
description:
Situated on the Cowal peninsula in the west of Scotland, Pucks Glen is a popular walk centred on a deep wooded gorge with beautiful waterfalls and dark forest paths.
This shot was taken near the highest point of the glen.

*LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: Pucks Glen, Scotland
description:
Situated on the Cowal peninsula in the west of Scotland, Pucks Glen is a popular walk centred on a deep wooded gorge with beautiful waterfalls and dark forest paths.
This shot was taken near the base of the glen.

*LIMITED EDITION (100 print run max):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame.

name: Sunrise over Bishops Loch, Glasgow
description:
Taken just a few miles from Glasgow city centre, Bishops Loch is a part of a series of kettle ponds, formed towards the end of the last Ice Age by receding glaciers.

A male swan patrols the loch while a female sits on their nest and eggs

* LIMITED EDITION (100 Prints only):
12x12”print mounted on snow white card, signed and numbered by the photographer and framed in a 16x16” square black wooden frame
